english:
  title: Epitaph for the Late Minister of State Lee, Compiler of the Archives
  author: Choi Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Man receives his nature from the interplay of yin and yang. To be born is for the vital force to gather; when it disperses, death comes. In the span between, some prosper while others languish, some gain while others lose, some live long lives while others die young, some move swiftly through life while others lag behind—all according to what they were born to receive. There is nothing strange in this. Yet if one merely accepts this and does not cultivate oneself through practice, then one will rot away like grass and trees, leaving no trace, no sound. One becomes something less than human—unable to participate in the harmony of heaven and earth, unable to work wonders among all things.

    In ancient times, those who did not die in death achieved this through virtue or merit. Virtue is like a great mountain—still, unmoved—yet the world perceives only its smallest gleam, while its grace flows across the four seas. Merit springs forth where events converge, where thunder and wind clash together, where the people are lifted from the pit of suffering and the nation prospers. Then the body may withdraw into shadow, yet the Way grows ever more luminous; the deeds may fade into distance, yet the name shines ever brighter. Even a thousand years hence, the name rivals sun and moon in radiance. How then can the circumstances of one's rise and fall in the world be deemed worthy of discussion?

    I am old now, and I have witnessed much. I have seen what burns like flame and glows like sunlight—what moves us to love and fear—yet it takes but a turn of the heel for it to vanish completely. Before I could even inquire into their deeds, all is lost. What sorrow this is.

    Yet take Minister Lee of the Three Han realms: he was honored and esteemed throughout the land, and I myself once humbly followed in his wake. How could I hesitate to repay such debt? When his son approached me with his request for words to inscribe upon the tomb path, how could I dare to refuse?

    The Minister first entered service in the time of King Chungnyeol. The Grand Commander Wang—later King Chungseon—already recognized his talent and made him his attendant. Through long years of loyal service, his position rose and his renown grew. When the present king came to know him, he was specially appointed to the Chancellery, given the title of Scholar, and entrusted with counsel on matters of state. Serving four kings in all, he received the favor of each in turn, his standing never diminished. Such fortune could not have come without both literary grace and the power to move the hearts of rulers.

    The Minister's given name was Yanchung, with the courtesy name Lipji. His ancestral home was in Chongju, in Chonuiwon County. He was the nephew of that celebrated minister of our recent past, the one called Hun, who received the posthumous name Mun-jang. His grandfather was the late General of the Eagle Guard, named Ch'on, and his father was the late recipient of posthumous rank as Grand Protector, named Chwawon, who served in the Archives Bureau. His mother was the daughter of Kim Yuison, Inspector of the Military Arsenal, and received the title Lady of Yongga County.

    The Minister passed the examination of the Simja year as first place on the Samja examination, and again passed the examination of the Kapa year. Beginning as Recorder of the Palace of Xinxin, he advanced through many posts: Assistant in the Military Bureau, Counselor-in-Chief and Grand Protector heading the Academy of Worthies, Compiler of Edicts, Counselor of the Highest Rank and Inspector of the Ministry of Selection, prefect of various provinces, and finally Vice Director of the Chancellery, Senior Guard, Bearer of the Highest Rank, Minister of State and Scholar—positions of such dignity that one sees in them the whole arc of a lifetime in service.

    He married twice: first the Lady of Huapin County, daughter of the late Counselor Kim Hui, and later the Lady of Kangnin County, daughter of the current Commissioner of Military Affairs for the Capital and provinces, Hong Sui. From the first marriage came three sons: the late Lieutenant of the Tiger Guard Kwanggi, the late Guard Officer Kwangyik, and the late Registrar of the Ceremonial Bureau Sajol. From the second came Sanwon, now grown to manhood, and Sambo, who is but ten years old. His daughters married into prominent families: Minneu, now Counselor and Vice Minister; Yi Ulyun, military commander; Won Ho, the late officer; and Yun Huiho.

    He was born in the year Kyeyu, and departed this life on the day Kyongsu! of the tenth month in the year Muin. He was buried on the day Chongyu of the twelfth month of that same year.

    The epitaph reads:

    When the noble man yet dwelled among us,
    His spirit shone radiant and bright;
    We believed his fortune would grow ever more abundant.
    Now that the noble man has departed,
    We gaze at the vast emptiness—what can we say?
    Truly, human life knows no constancy.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem's final lines use celestial imagery to reflect on mortality and the transience of human fortune, a common theme in Korean funerary epitaphs of this period.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'four kings' indicates that Minister Lee served under four successive rulers, which was considered a mark of exceptional political skill and moral integrity.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Three Han realms' is an honorific reference to Korea, recalling the ancient Three Kingdoms period and emphasizing the official's status as a national figure.
